<h2>Functional Causality for Modeling Causal Relationships</h2>
   <p>  In order to analyze causal relations, we develop the notion
 of <em>functional causes</em>, a rigorous and extensible definition of 
causality. This definition builds upon the well-studied definition of <em>actual
 causes</em> by Halpern and Pearl, but enhances it in subtle ways, 
notably by encoding the semantics of causal network with the help of 
powerful <em>potential functions</em> and extending the original 
definition with several desirable and intuitive properties of causality.</p>

    <p> These properties allow us to define the causes of query results and
 their individual contributions in several ways: (i) we can model both <em>provenance</em>
 as well as <em>non-answers</em>, (ii) we can define explanations as 
either <em>data</em> in the input relations or relational <em>operations</em>
 in a query plan, and (iii) we can give graded degrees of responsibility
 to individual causes, thus allowing us to <em>rank causes</em>. In 
particular, our approach allows us to explain contributions to 
relational <em>aggregate functions</em> and to rank causes according to 
their respective <em>responsibilities</em>.</p> 

    
    
   

